To achieve the desired functionality of marking specific dates in a Calendar control, you can handle the `DayRender` event and modify the visual appearance of the desired dates.

Here's an example of how you can do this:

```csharp
private void calendarControl_DayRender(object sender, DayRenderEventArgs e)
{
    DateTime[] importantDates = new DateTime[]
    {
        new DateTime(2022, 1, 12),
        new DateTime(2022, 1, 21),
        new DateTime(2022, 2, 5),
    };

    if (importantDates.Contains(e.Day.Date))
    {
        e.Cell.BackColor = Color.Yellow;
        e.Cell.ForeColor = Color.Black;
        e.Cell.Font.Bold = true;
    }
}
```

In this example, the `DayRender` event is handled. Inside the event handler, you can define an array `importantDates` to represent the dates you want to mark.

For each day being rendered, it is checked whether the date is present in the `importantDates` array using the `Contains()` method. If it is found, the background color of the cell is set to `Color.Yellow`, the foreground color (text color) is set to `Color.Black`, and the font is set to bold using `Font.Bold`.

Make sure to subscribe to the `DayRender` event of the Calendar control either in the designer or programmatically using `calendarControl.DayRender += calendarControl_DayRender;`.

By using this approach, the specified dates will be visually marked in the Calendar control with a yellow background, black text, and bold font.

To prevent clicks on specific dates in a Calendar control and keep them selected, you can handle the `DayRender` event and disable the clickable behavior for those dates. Here's an example:

```csharp
private void calendarControl_DayRender(object sender, DayRenderEventArgs e)
{
    DateTime[] selectedDates = new DateTime[]
    {
        new DateTime(2022, 1, 12),
        new DateTime(2022, 1, 21),
        new DateTime(2022, 2, 5),
    };

    if (selectedDates.Contains(e.Day.Date))
    {
        e.Cell.Attributes["onclick"] = "return false";
        e.Cell.Style["cursor"] = "default";
    }
}
```

In this example, the `DayRender` event is handled. Inside the event handler, an array `selectedDates` is defined to represent the dates that should not be clickable.

For each day being rendered, it is checked whether the date is present in the `selectedDates` array using the `Contains()` method. If it is found, the `onclick` attribute of the cell is set to `"return false"` to disable the click event for that date. Additionally, the cursor style is set to `"default"` to indicate that the date is not clickable.

Make sure to subscribe to the `DayRender` event of the Calendar control either in the designer or programmatically using `calendarControl.DayRender += calendarControl_DayRender;`.

By using this approach, the specified dates will be visually selected in the Calendar control and the user won't be able to click on them. Other dates will remain clickable.

