If you want to prevent clicks on any date in the `System.Windows.Forms.Calendar` control, one workaround is to handle the `MouseDown` event and cancel the event for each day. Here's an example:

```csharp
private void calendarControl_MouseDown(object sender, MouseEventArgs e)
{
    calendarControl.SelectionStart = calendarControl.HitTest(e.X, e.Y).Time;
    calendarControl.SelectionEnd = calendarControl.SelectionStart;
    calendarControl.Invalidate();
    calendarControl.ActiveMonth.MonthlyCalendar_MouseDown(null);
}
```

In this example, the `MouseDown` event is handled for the `System.Windows.Forms.Calendar` control. It sets the selection start to the clicked day and clears the selection end. Then, it invalidates the control to trigger a repaint and calls the `MouseDown` event handler of the `MonthlyCalendar` (inner control of the `Calendar` control) to handle the click event.

Make sure to subscribe to the `MouseDown` event of the `Calendar` control either in the designer or programmatically using `calendarControl.MouseDown += calendarControl_MouseDown;`.

This approach prevents the user from manually selecting any date in the `Calendar` control through clicks. However, it does not disable the keyboard navigation or programmatically selecting dates.

