To prevent clicks on the dates in the `Calendar` control while allowing the user to change the month, you can handle the `PreviewMouseLeftButtonDown` event for the `CalendarDayButton` specifically. This way, you can cancel the event only when the user clicks on a date, not on the header or other navigation elements.

Here's an example:

```csharp
private void calendarControl_PreviewMouseLeftButtonDown(object sender, MouseButtonEventArgs e)
{
    var originalSource = e.OriginalSource as DependencyObject;
    var calendarDayButton = FindParent<CalendarDayButton>(originalSource);
    if (calendarDayButton != null)
    {
        e.Handled = true;
    }
}

private static T FindParent<T>(DependencyObject dependencyObject) where T : DependencyObject
{
    var parent = VisualTreeHelper.GetParent(dependencyObject);
    if (parent == null)
        return null;

    var parentT = parent as T;
    return parentT ?? FindParent<T>(parent);
}
```

In this example, the `PreviewMouseLeftButtonDown` event is handled for the `Calendar` control. By using the `FindParent` helper method, it checks if the original source of the event is a `CalendarDayButton` (a date button). If it is, the event is cancelled by setting `e.Handled` to `true`.

Make sure to subscribe to the `PreviewMouseLeftButtonDown` event of the `Calendar` control either in the XAML markup or programmatically using `calendarControl.PreviewMouseLeftButtonDown += calendarControl_PreviewMouseLeftButtonDown;`.

By using this approach, the user can still change the month and navigate through the calendar, but clicks on the dates will be prevented.
